expert_comments.text:
It may also be interesting to see how much the upper bound in [Theorem 2, EPS87] can be improved. Almost trivially, by taking instead 
\begin{align*}
l&=\exp\left(c_0((\log x)(\log\log x)(\log\log\log x))^{1/3}\right),\\
L&=\exp\left(c_1((\log x)(\log\log x))^{2/3}(\log\log\log x)^{-1/3}\right),
\end{align*}
with suitable constants $c_0,c_1>0$ in their proof, and using Theorem 1.1 in this paper by Banks et al. (2018) to handle (iv), one can show that the number of $n\le x$ with $\phi(n)=\phi(n+1)$ is at most\[x\exp\left(-c_0((\log x)(\log\log x)(\log\log\log x))^{1/3}\right).\]
